frameDefinitions: A Self_mover leaves an initial Source location.
A Competition comes to an end, with a Competitor tying, winning, or losing against an Opponent (or opponents) according to their Score.
The words in this frame have to do with people and the personal Relationships they are or can be a part of.
A Supporter assists to strengthen the Supported by lending itself in material aid (or abstract assistance in the case of metaphorical uses).
This frame describes a situation in which an Owner loses his or her Possession.
These are words describing situations in which a Perpetrator takes Goods from a  Victim or a Source.
frameExamples: Unbelievable--he <t>lost</t> the gold medal by just .02 points!
And of course that drippy <t><fex name='Partner_1'>boyfriend</fex></t> of hers backed her up.
The bottom of the wall is <t>supported</t> by the foundation.
I can't believe he <t>pickpocketed</t> my gold watch !
listRoleDefinitions: This is the entity which moves under its own power.

Any expression which implies a definite starting-point of motion expresses the frame element <fen>Source</fen>. In prepositional phrases, the prepositional object expresses the starting point of motion. In particles, the starting point of motion is understood from context.
The time at which the motion takes place.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the motion (which is specified by a <fen>Source</fen>, <fen>Path</fen> or <fen>Goal</fen>) is located.
The individual involved in the <fen>Competition</fen>.
The individual that the <fen>Competitor</fen> has been competing against.
The individuals who compete against each other.
The event in which the <fen>Competitors</fen> compete with each other.
The time at which the <fen>Competition</fen> takes place.
The location at which the <fen>Competition</fen> takes place.
That partner in the <fen>Relationship</fen> who is realized as the subject of verbs in active form sentences, or of adjectives in predicative uses.
That partner in the <fen>Relationship</fen> who is not expressed as the external argument.
The joint construal of both <fen>Partners</fen> in the <fen>Relationship</fen>.
The <fen>Supporter</fen> acts to benefit the <fex name='Supported'>Supported</fex> by providing additional strength or stability.
The <fen>Supported</fen> is given strength through the assistance of the <fen>Supporter</fen>.
This role identifies when the support occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the support occurs.
The original <fen>Owner</fen> of the <fen>Possession</fen>.
The object that is possessed by the <fen>Owner</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Possession</fen> is lost.
The <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Possession</fen> is lost.
<fen>Perpetrator</fen> is the person (or other agent) that takes the goods away.
<fen>Victim</fen> is the person (or other sentient being or group) that owns the goods before they are taken away by the perpetrator.
<fen>Goods</fen> is anything (including labor, time, or legal rights) that can be taken away.
<fen>Source</fen> is the initial location of the goods, before they change location.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the theft occurs.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the theft occurs.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Early in the twentieth century</fex>, such economic arguments buttressed the creation of a National Park Service.
<fex>In England</fex>, economic incentives are buttressed by closing certain overdoctored areas from new practices.
Leslie stole the watch <fex>from the table</fex>.
Leslie STOLE the watch from Kim <fex>at dusk</fex>.
Leslie STOLE the watch from Kim <fex>in the park</fex>.
